<h1>
COLLEGE OF ARTS &amp; SCIENCES
<br/>ASIAN LANGUAGES AND LITERATURE
<br/>SOUTH ASIA
</h1>

<p>Detailed course offerings (Time Schedule) are available for<ul>

<li><a href="/students/timeschd/WIN2024/sasian.html">Winter Quarter 2024</a></li>

<li><a href="/students/timeschd/SPR2024/sasian.html">Spring Quarter 2024</a></li>

</ul></p>

<a name="sasia203"><p><b>S ASIA 203 Love and War in Classical Indian Literature (5) SSc/A&amp;H</b><br/>Introduction to enduring themes of love and war in classical Indian literature in its cultural context with a specific focus on contemporary relevance, including popular culture. Texts in English translation.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA203" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 203</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia206"><p><b>S ASIA 206 Modern Literature of South Asia (5) A&amp;H/SSc</b><br/>Introduction to the modern literature of South Asia (India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal), from the eighteenth century to the present. Readings include a selection of novels, short stories, and poetry drawn from the diverse literary traditions of the region and placed in their cultural contexts. All texts in English translation.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA206" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 206</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia225"><p><b>S ASIA 225 Indian Philosophical Literature (5) A&amp;H/SSc</b><br/>Introduction to various topics pertaining to the vast philosophical literature of India, such as its origins and contexts, dharma; karma and free will; logic and argument. A variety of systems from Hindu, Buddhist, Jain, theistic, and non-theistic schools are covered. Taught in English. Offered: WS.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA225" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 225</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia254"><p><b>S ASIA 254 Fairies, Genies, and Monsters: The Romance Genre in India (5) A&amp;H</b><br/>Introduction to the long adventure narratives (dastan) of South Asia, with reference to the Middle and Near East. Texts in English translation.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA254" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 254</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia316"><p><b>S ASIA 316 Postcolonial Literature of South Asia (5) A&amp;H, DIV</b><br/>Surveys postcolonial literature in South Asia from 1947 to the present.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA316" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 316</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia498"><p><b>S ASIA 498 Special Topics in Languages and Cultures of South Asia (1-5, max. 18) A&amp;H</b><br/>Topics vary. Offered: AWSpS.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA498" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 498</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia499"><p><b>S ASIA 499 Undergraduate Research (3-5, max. 15)</b><br/>Undergraduate research/independent study in South Asian languages and cultures. Offered: AWSpS.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA499" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 499</a></p></a>
<a name="sasia585"><p><b>S ASIA 585 Radical Fictions: Literary Modernisms in South Asia (5)</b><br/>Surveys the development of literary modernism in South Asia. Introduces major thinkers, writers, and centers for literary modernism in colonial and postcolonial South Asia.<br/><a href="https://myplan.washington.edu/course/#/courses/S ASIA585" target="_blank">View course details in MyPlan: S ASIA 585</a></p></a>

